title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger LC9
location: Virginia Beach Ocenafront, Hampton Roads, Virginia
postcontent:
A LITTLE BIGGER, A LITTLE BETTER
 Designed for discreet concealment, the LC9 can serve either as a primary citizen-carry tool or a full-power backup for off-duty law enforcement officers. In most respects it is simply a slightly larger single-column twin to the .380 LCP. It’s larger because it has to be, both because the 9mm cartridge is slightly longer than the .380 Auto and requires a deeper grip frame and action cycle and because the 9mm’s increased recoil requires more grasping surface (and weight) for controllability.  The somewhat larger LC9 goes naturally into my hand and is a true grab-and-shoot gun. In size it comes about midway between the LCP and the midsize double-column Ruger SR9 Compact (but it’s closer to the LCP).

The LC9 has a 3.1-inch barrel and is only six inches long and 41/2 inches tall, making for a very compact 9mm. With a width of a mere .90 inch, it’s one of the slimmest-profile 9mms on the market. It weighs only 17.1 ounces with an empty magazine.

The glass-filled nylon black polymer grip frame with blued alloy-steel slide and barrel utilizes an aluminum locking block insert. Each gun comes with one seven-round, single-column magazine with a standard flat floorplate for maximum concealability. An interchangeable finger-grip extension floorplate is also provided as an accessory for shooters who prefer a longer grip surface with more hand-to-pistol contact.

This pistol comes with an additional 7 rd factory magazine and an extended 10 rd magazine. Original Box and nylon case as well. 


Read more: http://www.gunsandammo.com/reviews/rugers-lc9-powered-up-pocket-protection/#ixzz333t7FlAA

title: For Sale:  FN FAL Israeli Heavy Barrel
postcontent: Nice Israeli heavy barrel FN FAL rifle with Belgian lower receiver, bolt, and carier. Barrel is chrome lined Israeli dated 1970. Wood furniture is new. Manganese phosphate parkerizing. Recever was engraved with the IDF crest and other manufacturer marking to mimic an original. Does not appear to have been fired much since it was built. I estimate this rifle was built in 2008. This rifle was part of Pat Jones personal collection and was the first to feature the Israeli engraving he offered.  I believe this rifle to be almost unfired since it was built.
